			<h4><a id="comment_link_64534193" name="comment_link_64534193" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23350035&amp;cid=64534193" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64534193)" >Nuclear's time was 40+ years ago</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64534193" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64534193); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>3</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~locater16">locater16</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~locater16">( 2326718 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64534193">		
		on Saturday June 08, 2024 @06:50PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23350035&amp;cid=64534193">#64534193</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64534193">The nuclear industry has certainly tried to pep up it's image, and it's been quite successful in the image department. Multiple people quote the "Facts" that Chernobyl "wasn't that bad a disaster". Ignoring that tens of thousands of people lost their home and an entire region of Ukraine is uninhabitable. Quoting industry nonsense that "not that many people died" when recent cancer studies clearly show it's likely easily the greatest loss of life due to an increase in cancer rates of any industrial disaster in human history by an order of magnitude: <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10436126/" title="nih.gov">https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/p...</a> [nih.gov]
<br> <br>
What the nuclear industry has not managed to do is shill away the miserable economics of nuclear power. No bribing of economics professors to give overly simplistic explanations of how "nuclear is cheap actually" nor constantly delivering <a href="https://dspace.mit.edu/bitstream/handle/1721.1/133049/Jacopo's%20and%20Jessika's%20paper%20on%20nuclear%20cost%20Sep%202020.pdf" title="mit.edu">deliberately skewed price quotes</a> [mit.edu] changes the fact that solar is dirt cheap and only getting cheaper. Nor that batteries, one of the hottest industries on the planet, are likely to be cheap enough to make 24/7 solar power cheaper than nuclear by the time their "revolution" kicks in in any meaningful way, nor that if one wanted to bet on future power delivery fusion startups offer timelines not that dissimilar to "new" nuclear reactor designs but with vastly more potential for returns.
<br> <br>
Nuclear is a dead end, if it was going to save us from climate change the time was decades ago. Today there are much better prospects, and everyone but the nuclear industry itself and easily conned politicians and self styled internet experts knows it.</div>
	</div>

